rytelling often carries as much argumentative weight within a judgement as the logic of legal distinctions. Through their narrative choices, Henderson argues, judges create a normative universe – the world of right and wrong within which they make their judgements – and fashion their own judicial self-images. Drawing on the work of the law and literature movement, Creating Legal Worlds is a convincing argument for paying close attention to the role of story and style in the creation of judicial decisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aForensic orations. 0aLaw and literature. 0aLawxLanguage. 0aRhetoric. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262450440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442624504423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442624504.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles